section.section:
Except as provided in subsection (e) of this section, if an insurer offers to a beneficiary a retained asset account as a settlement option, the insurer shall provide to the beneficiary in writing:
a recommendation to consult a tax advisor, an investment advisor, or any other financial advisor regarding tax liability and investment options;
an explanation of the features of the retained asset account, including:
the method used to determine interest rates applied to the retained asset account, when and how interest rates may change, and any dividends and other gains that may be paid or distributed to the account holder;
the custodian of the funds or assets of the retained asset account;
whether the funds in the retained asset account are guaranteed by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) and the amount of the coverage, if any;
the limitations, if any, on the numbers and amounts of withdrawals of funds from the retained asset account or investment, including any minimum or maximum withdrawal amounts;
the services provided for a fee, including a list of the fees or the method of their calculation;
the nature and frequency of statements of account;
a statement that the obligation of the insurer to pay the total policy or contract proceeds is satisfied by depositing the total proceeds in the retained asset account;
a statement that the entire proceeds are available to the account holder by the use of one check, draft, or other instrument;
a statement that the insurer or a related party may derive income, in addition to any fees charged on the retained asset account, from the total gains received on the investment of the balance of funds in the retained asset account; and
the telephone number, address, and other contact information, including Web site address, for obtaining additional information regarding the retained asset account; and
the statement "For further information, please contact your state insurance department".
